Hi Frederico,

I'd recommend doing something like this:

``` javascript
var images = [
    "image1.jpg",
    "image2.jpg",
    "image3.jpg"
];

var index = 0;
$.backstretch(images[index], {speed: 500});

var slideshow = setInterval(function() {
    index = (index >= images.length - 1) ? 0 : index + 1;
    $.backstretch(images[index]);
}, 5000);

$("a.clickable").click(function(e) {
    // Prevent the click from actually following the href
    e.preventDefault();

    // Stop the slideshow
    clearInterval(slideshow);

    // Backstretch
    $.backstretch( $(this).attr("href") );
});
```

And, then for your thumbnails, I'd make them look like this:

``` html
<a class="clickable" href="image1.jpg"><img src="image1_thumb.jpg"/></a>
<a class="clickable" href="image2.jpg"><img src="image2_thumb.jpg"/></a>
<a class="clickable" href="image3.jpg"><img src="image3_thumb.jpg"/></a>
```

As you can see, there's now a "clickable" class, so that all of your links can share the same code. Also, I've added the image that you want to backstretch to as the href tag. This way, if JavaScript fails, it will still link the user to that image.

Hope you find this helpful. If you need any additional help, please consider purchasing Premium Support for Backstretch (located at the bottom of the page).

http://srobbin.com/blog/jquery-plugins/jquery-backstretch/

Cheers,
Scott

