I hacked the two together. Well, I used cycle in its entirety, and I just lifted a little bit of the code from backstretch. It's pretty messy and tightly coupled (not in plugin form), but it works and gets the general idea down. `.slideshow` contained all of my different slideshows (I had multiple slideshows per page), `.slider` is a single instance of a slideshow and the element cycle is called on, `.slide` is the container element for each slide, and finally `.slideBg` is the container with the image that needs to be resized (I had some other elements in each slide that I didn't want to have resized).

I also had to accommodate for additional spacing in some cases. At times the design called for full screen width, minus 530px, or full height, minus 150px.

If you don't care about perfectly centering the image so it's cropped evenly on the top/bottom or left/right, then you can simply use cycle with the images set to `min-width:100%; min-height:100%;` I believe you might need `width:100%; height:100%;` on the containing element or the html & body iirc.

Here's the main part of the code to achieve the backstretch effect. The code I used from backstretch is inside the load event.

``` javascript
$(window).resize(function(){
    myDimensions = {
        width: $(window).width(), //$('body')[0].clientWidth,
        height: window.innerHeight ? window.innerHeight : $(window).height() -150
    };

    $('.slideshow').height(myDimensions.height - heightAdjustment);
    $('.slideBg').css(myDimensions).filter('.column').css({ width: myDimensions.width - 530});

    $(".slideBg").each(function(i, el){
        var $slideBg = $(this),
            slideWidth  = $(this).width(),
            slideHeight = $(this).height(),

            $img = $slideBg.find('img'),
            src  = $img.attr('src'),
            imgObj = new Image(),
            imgWidth,
            imgHeight,
            imgRatio,

            bgWidth,
            bgHeight,
            offset,
            bgCSS = {left: 0, top: 0};


            // Bind the load event before setting the src to get rid of caching inconsistencies
        $(imgObj).load(function(){
            imgWidth  = imgObj.width,
            imgHeight = imgObj.height;
            imgRatio  = imgWidth / imgHeight;

            bgWidth  = slideWidth;
            bgHeight = bgWidth / imgRatio;

            if(bgHeight >= slideHeight){
                offset = (bgHeight - slideHeight) / 2;
                bgCSS.top = '-'+offset+'px';
            } else {
                bgHeight = slideHeight;
                bgWidth  = bgHeight * imgRatio;
                offset   = (bgWidth - slideWidth) / 2;
                bgCSS.left = '-'+offset+'px';
            }

            $img.css({width: bgWidth, height: bgHeight}).css(bgCSS);

        }).attr('src', src);
    });
}).resize();
```

Followed by normal instantiation of Cycle, with `slideResize: false`

