If you want to do a responsive-like image for the current browser window height/width, you'll need to do something like:

``` javascript
function getWidth() {
    if (window.innerWidth) {
        return window.innerWidth;
    } else if (document.documentElement && document.documentElement.clientWidth) {
        return document.documentElement.clientWidth; //IE 7, 8
    }
}
```

then replace window.screen.width above with getWidth().

window.screen.width will always return the same value no matter what your browser window is sized to which is fine if all you want to do is find out if you are on a mobile device of a particular size, but it may not be what you want if your user is on a PC and they just happen to have their browser window sized below one of your breakpoints. If you don't care about IE<9, instead of getWidth() just use window.innerWidth.

