You could use [jQuery Browser Plugin](https://github.com/gabceb/jquery-browser-plugin) to detect the device and then just use a simple if statement to define the image.

``` javascript
var backgroundsrc = ($.browser.mobile == true) ? 'path/to/mobile/image.jpg' : 'path/to/desktop/image.jpg';

$('#element').backstretch(backgroundsrc);
```

If you require it work for multiple images you could always put the path to the images in data attributes on the elements.

```
<div class="backstretchelement" data-mobile="path/to/mobile/image.jpg" data-desktop="path/to/desktop/image.jpg"></div>
```

``` javascript
$('.backstretchelement').each(function(event){
    var imagesize = ($.browser.mobile == true) ? 'mobile' : 'desktop';
    $(this).backstretch($(this).data(imagesize));
});
```

